<a href="#product-update" name="product-update"></a><table width="600" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" class="full-block" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" ><table cellpadding="40" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="middle" class="text-block" style="padding-bottom:10px; color:#666666; font-size:13px; line-height:22px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="product-update-title" style="padding-bottom:20px; " ><img style="display: block;" src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/claudenl-portrait.png" alt="Anthony" align="right"> <span style="color: #666666; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16px;">PRODUCT UPDATE</span><br> <span style="margin: 0; font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 24px; text-transform: uppercase;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-e92b2559-6671-674d-5341-68b630d91b08"><span>Meet PCF Dev—PCF from Your Desktop</span></span></span><br> <span style="color: #666666; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px;">Claude Devarenne, Advisory Field Engineer</span></div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="top" class="stack" style="color:#666666; font-size:14px; line-height:22px; padding-bottom:20px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="product-update-entry" >
<p><span id="docs-internal-guid-e92b2559-6672-455c-f8bd-53dc8b74f6dd"> </span></p>
<p class="normal">Say you're a developer who seeks to develop and debug applications locally on a full-featured Cloud Foundry, or you just want to get your feet wet with Cloud Foundry, but don't have access to a foundation yet.
  What do you do? <br /><br /> <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://github.com/pivotal-cf/pcfdev">PCF Dev</a> is a new Cloud Foundry distribution that lets you&mdash;the developer&mdash;run Cloud Foundry on your laptop or workstation.
  It's the simplest way to get a complete Cloud Foundry on a single machine, with the same automation and velocity as found on PCF.
  <br /><br /> PCF Dev runs atop <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://www.vagrantup.com/docs/why-vagrant/">Vagrant</a>, a popular tool for sharing environments.
  Currently in beta, developers can download PFC Dev from the <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://network.pivotal.io/">Pivotal Network</a>, and for now it's only available to Pivotal Cloud Foundry customers.
   <br /><br /> The tool makes it easy for any developer to try things out with Cloud Foundry, and in most cases, the code you write and deploy to PCF Dev will work just the same in a full blown Pivotal Cloud Foundry foundation.
  Customers are interested, and I have recommended PCF Dev to customer developer teams to get them started quickly and easily.
  <br /><br /> As lightweight as it is, PCF Dev still provides a rich experience because your application can bind to a host of services, including Redis, RabbitMQ and MySQL.
  You can also create and bind to user-provided services, such as a service of your own that you run locally.
  <br /><br /> PCF Dev is an impressive concentration of Cloud Foundry capabilities, and our <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="https://github.com/pivotal-cf/pcfdev/blob/master/FAQ.md#general-questions">FAQ</a> provides the documentation and all you need to know to get customers started.
  <br /><br /> For our field teams and platform architects, PCF Dev can be the environment from which they deliver hands-on workshops to customers.
  The best part is that once the workshop is over, participants still have access to the environment on their machines and they can continue to work with it.
  Let the PCF Dev team know (<strong>#pcfdev</strong> on Slack, or <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="mailto:pcfdev-eng@pivotal.io">pcfdev-eng@pivotal.io</a>) if your customers are interested in PCF Dev.</p>
</div>
