<a href="#people-update" name="people-update"></a><table width="600" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" class="full-block" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" ><table cellpadding="40" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="middle" class="text-block" style="padding-bottom:10px; color:#666666; font-size:13px; line-height:22px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="people-update-title" style="padding-bottom:20px; " ><img style="display: block;" src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/maryamlabib-nl-portrait.png" alt="Maria" align="right"><span style="color: #666666; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16px;">PEOPLE UPDATE</span><br> <span style="margin: 0; font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 24px; text-transform: uppercase;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-e92b2559-6678-2edb-d7be-ad35822620b9"><span><span id="docs-internal-guid-c78ad48f-38f4-09c9-4adc-dfa4089374d1"><span><span id="docs-internal-guid-dfe2020a-a588-171b-b662-6e03c9e0d265"><span>Women Transforming Tech: Work, Life, and Finding Success</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><br> <span style="color: #666666; font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-dfe2020a-a589-43b4-f600-b70e6448e959"><span>Maryam Labib, Software Engineer</span></span><br></span></div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; " ><tr ><td align="left" valign="top" class="stack" style="color:#666666; font-size:14px; line-height:22px; padding-bottom:20px; " ><div class="mktEditable" id="people-update-entry" >
<p class="normal">At the <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="http://www.womentransformingtechnology.com/">Women Transforming Technology</a> (WT2) Conference held in Palo Alto in late February, keynote speaker Arianna Huffington, co-founder and editor-in-chief of <a style="color: #059a91; text-decoration: none;" href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/">The Huffington Post</a>,   
cut to the chase: "There are two obstacles that impede women's success." While external factors in male-dominated workplaces such as sexism and exclusion are well recognized, the silent killers are the internal monologues that churn endlessly in women's minds and drain their energy.
   "I couldn't perform at my full capacity.
   So I had to evict the obnoxious roommate." She referenced the Michel de Montaigne quote, "There were many terrible things in my life but most have never happened." <br /><br /> I actually didn't learn about WT2 until two days before.
   Pivotal colleagues (thank you David Stevenson and team) did their magic to get me the spot of someone who had dropped out, and one e-mail to the D&amp;I list later, I had friends to go with.
   <br /><br /> WT2 was a cozy conference of about 300 attendees; many were employees at the sponsoring companies, Pivotal, EMC, VMWare, and Intuit.
   The program of the one-day conference consisted of two keynote speeches, with breakout tracks on leadership, new to your career, technical.
   There was also a diversity track that was invite-only (the irony was not lost on us).
   <br /><br /> Arianna's talk received a standing ovation.
   While she focused on women and technology, she had a broader message about the hard lessons learned in building a sustainable career.
   "Workplaces were designed by men." If they had been designed by/along with women, they would have accommodated the flexibility of people's schedules while getting even more productivity out of them.
   "Why has work become so unsustainable and so damaging to our health?" she asked a crowd of nodding heads.
   "It's not like the people who are working themselves to the ground are making good decisions." She cited famous CEOs who died young from stress while others meditate and get eight hours of sleep.
   Some companies make their employees go to yoga classes or take naps.
   "When people are happier, they want to be at work more, and they give more back." <br /><br /> Arianna realized that the Silicon Valley lifestyle was slowly killing her after she collapsed in a meeting.
   "I was exhausted, and I didn't like the person I had become." When she started to improve her quality of life, her anger and over reactiveness became replaced with calmness and enjoyment.
   "Get more done by improving your capacity for joy." <br /><br /> The meaning of 'leadership' in the Silicon Valley has become synonymous with being busy.
   "Leadership isn't always answering your emails immediately.
   It's about seeing the iceberg before it hits the titanic." She said that often our sleep-deprivation and anxiety cause us to actually make harmful short-term work decisions.
   "We are assaulted by technology.
   We're taking better care of our smartphones than ourselves.
   We cannot achieve because our smartphones are invading our lives.
   We need to take back control." <br /><br /> Arianna then talked about shoes and sleep for the next 30 minutes, but I will summarize it for you.
   Get at least 8 hours of sleep, stop using technology 30 minutes before you hit the pillow, and have a bedtime ritual.
   Oh.
   And don't wear high heels.
   You are welcome.
   <br /><br /> <img src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/peopleupdate1v4n4.jpg" alt="Arianna Huffington" width="500" /><br /><img src="http://connect.pivotal.io/rs/625-IUJ-009/images/peopleupdate2v4n4.jpg" alt="WT2 attendees" width="500" /><br /><em><span style="font-size: 10px;">WT2 (top to bottom): Arianna Huffington in motion; Attendees and leaders tune in.</span></em><br 
/><br /> The common sentiment  expressed by all speakers was how we should lead happy, ambitious lives, and use technology to make a lasting difference in the world.
   As Arianna concluded, "It's kind of amazing how the way our life is talked about after we die is so different from our LinkedIn profile.
   And shouldn't we align the two more?"</p>
